Math and Collision

This page provides an overview of the mathematical primitives and collision detection systems in MonoGame. It covers vector types, matrix operations, quaternions, and various collision structures that enable spatial testing for games such as bounding volumes, rays, and planes.

Overview

MonoGame includes a comprehensive suite of mathematical structures to handle vector math, transformations, and collision detection. These components serve as the foundation for:

  • Representing positions, directions, and velocities (vectors)
  • Handling rotations, scaling, and coordinate system transformations (matrices and quaternions)
  • Detecting intersections between game objects (collision primitives)
  • Implementing spatial queries such as ray casting

Vector Structures

MonoGame provides several vector types to represent positions and directions in different dimensions.

Vector2, Vector3, and Vector4

These structures represent points or directions in 2D, 3D, and 4D space respectively, using floating-point coordinates.

All vector types support basic operations:

  • Addition and subtraction
  • Multiplication and division (scalar and component-wise)
  • Normalization
  • Dot product
  • Common helper methods (distance, lerp, min/max, etc.)

Vector3 additionally provides cross product operations and predefined constants for common directions (Up, Down, Forward, etc.).

Sources:

  • MonoGame.Framework/Vector2.cs20-233
  • MonoGame.Framework/Vector3.cs20-148
  • MonoGame.Framework/Vector4.cs19-107

Point and Rectangle

Point represents integer coordinates in 2D space, primarily used for screen positions and pixel-precise locations. Rectangle represents a 2D rectangle with integer coordinates, commonly used for UI elements, sprites, and 2D collision detection.

Rectangle provides methods for:

  • Containment tests (points, vectors, other rectangles)
  • Intersection tests with other rectangles
  • Inflation (expanding rectangle size)
  • Creating unions or intersections of rectangles

Sources:

  • MonoGame.Framework/Point.cs17-233
  • MonoGame.Framework/Rectangle.cs16-364

Matrix and Quaternion

Matrix

Matrix represents a 4×4 matrix primarily used for transformations in 3D space. It can represent translation, rotation, scaling, and projection operations.

Key Matrix functionalities:

  • Creation of transformation matrices (translation, rotation, scaling)
  • Creation of view and projection matrices
  • Matrix multiplication and inversion
  • Decomposition into components
  • Access to direction vectors (Right, Up, Forward, etc.)

Sources:

  • MonoGame.Framework/Matrix.cs16-187
  • MonoGame.Framework/Matrix.cs279-407
  • MonoGame.Framework/Matrix.cs632-753
  • MonoGame.Framework/Matrix.cs762-896

Quaternion

Quaternion represents rotations in 3D space using a 4D vector (X, Y, Z, W). Quaternions avoid gimbal lock issues that can occur with Euler angles and are more efficient for certain operations than rotation matrices.

Key Quaternion functionalities:

  • Creation from axis-angle representation
  • Creation from yaw, pitch, roll angles
  • Creation from rotation matrix
  • Interpolation between rotations (Slerp, Lerp)
  • Normalization and inversion

Sources:

  • MonoGame.Framework/Quaternion.cs16-104
  • MonoGame.Framework/Quaternion.cs267-289
  • MonoGame.Framework/Quaternion.cs301-302
  • MonoGame.Framework/Quaternion.cs735-752

Bounding Volumes

MonoGame provides several bounding volume types for collision detection and spatial queries.

Bounding Box

BoundingBox represents an axis-aligned bounding box (AABB) in 3D space, defined by minimum and maximum points.

Key BoundingBox functionalities:

  • Containment tests with other bounding volumes
  • Intersection tests with rays and other bounding volumes
  • Creation from points, spheres, or other boxes
  • Merging boxes to create a containing box
  • Retrieving corner points

Sources:

  • MonoGame.Framework/BoundingBox.cs17-88
  • MonoGame.Framework/BoundingBox.cs68-232
  • MonoGame.Framework/BoundingBox.cs384-447

Bounding Sphere

BoundingSphere represents a sphere in 3D space, defined by a center point and radius.

Key BoundingSphere functionalities:

  • Containment tests with other bounding volumes
  • Intersection tests with rays and other bounding volumes
  • Creation from points, boxes, or other spheres
  • Merging spheres to create a containing sphere

Sources:

  • MonoGame.Framework/BoundingSphere.cs17-61
  • MonoGame.Framework/BoundingSphere.cs74-234
  • MonoGame.Framework/BoundingSphere.cs245-257

Bounding Frustum

BoundingFrustum represents a view frustum, typically used for view culling. It's defined by a view-projection matrix.

Key BoundingFrustum functionalities:

  • Containment tests with other bounding volumes
  • Intersection tests with rays and other bounding volumes
  • Access to the six frustum planes
  • Retrieving corner points

Sources:

  • MonoGame.Framework/BoundingFrustum.cs14-101
  • MonoGame.Framework/BoundingFrustum.cs179-209

Rays and Planes

Ray

Ray represents a ray in 3D space, defined by an origin point and a direction vector.

Key Ray functionalities:

  • Intersection tests with bounding volumes and planes
  • Returns distance along the ray to intersection point, or null if no intersection

Sources:

  • MonoGame.Framework/Ray.cs16-46
  • MonoGame.Framework/Ray.cs97-178
  • MonoGame.Framework/Ray.cs228-246

Plane

Plane represents a plane in 3D space, defined by a normal vector and a distance from the origin.

Key Plane functionalities:

  • Various dot product calculations
  • Transformation by matrices and quaternions
  • Normalization
  • Intersection tests (through extension methods)

Sources:

  • MonoGame.Framework/Plane.cs43-129
  • MonoGame.Framework/Plane.cs141-273
  • MonoGame.Framework/Plane.cs278-284

Common Collision Patterns

Basic Bounding Box Collision

BoundingBox boxA = new BoundingBox(minA, maxA);
BoundingBox boxB = new BoundingBox(minB, maxB);

// Simple intersection test
bool colliding = boxA.Intersects(boxB);

// Containment test
ContainmentType containment = boxA.Contains(boxB);
switch (containment)
{
    case ContainmentType.Disjoint:
        // No collision
        break;
    case ContainmentType.Contains:
        // boxA completely contains boxB
        break;
    case ContainmentType.Intersects:
        // Partial overlap
        break;
}

Ray Casting

Ray ray = new Ray(origin, direction);
BoundingBox box = new BoundingBox(min, max);
BoundingSphere sphere = new BoundingSphere(center, radius);

// Returns distance to intersection or null if no intersection
float? distanceToBox = ray.Intersects(box);
float? distanceToSphere = ray.Intersects(sphere);

if (distanceToBox.HasValue)
{
    // Calculate intersection point
    Vector3 intersectionPoint = ray.Position + ray.Direction * distanceToBox.Value;
}

Sources:

  • MonoGame.Framework/BoundingBox.cs68-88
  • MonoGame.Framework/Ray.cs97-246

Best Practices

  1. Choose the right bounding volume - Use the simplest volume that adequately covers your objects:

    • BoundingBox for rectangular objects
    • BoundingSphere for approximately spherical objects or quick broad-phase checks
    • BoundingFrustum for view frustum culling

  2. Use a two-phase collision approach:

    • Broad phase: Use simple bounding volumes to quickly rule out distant objects
    • Narrow phase: Use more precise collision detection only on objects that passed the broad phase

  3. Optimize vector operations:

    • Use the ref parameter versions of methods for performance-critical code
    • Pre-compute and cache frequently used values

  4. Leverage built-in hierarchies:

    • Build bounding volume hierarchies for complex scenes
    • Prefer CreateFromPoints methods to ensure tight boundaries around models

  5. Update bounding volumes efficiently:

    • Transform bounding volumes along with their objects
    • For static objects, pre-compute bounding volumes once

Sources:

  • MonoGame.Framework/BoundingBox.cs384-447
  • MonoGame.Framework/BoundingSphere.cs245-257
